Fixed-line services, such as Comcast and Verizon’s fiber-optic service FiOS, also have to avoid “unreasonable discrimination” that slows or degrades traffic. The rules are more lax for mobile broadband, which doesn’t have to avoid unreasonable discrimination because mobile networks are subject to more competition and face tighter technological constraints.
